<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-522-154  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 522 154.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 4 1990 v24 n23 p78(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Douglas brings costs back to earth. (McDonnell-Douglas uses newmanufacturing system)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mason, Janet.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>McDonnell-Douglas Corp's Douglas Aircraft subsidiary uses a newintegrated Assembly Tracking and Management System (ATMS) computersystem at its manufacturing facilities in California, Ohio, SaltLake City, Long Beach and Macon, GA.andP;  ATMS helped Douglas Aircraftreturn to profitability after suffering operating losses of $52million in 1983.andP;  It lets assembly workers track entire factoryprocesses, including project delays, work assignments, and thecurrent status of each aircraft.andP;  ATMS resides on a Unisysmainframe in Long Beach linked via hyperchannel to an IBM 3090 andhas 14,000 users.andP;  The system is written in the Unisys Mapperfourth generation language and allows dramatic cost savingsthrough rapid prototyping.andP;  ATMS allows supervisors to prioritizework assignments and consistently review each day's work withoutspending hours creating schedules manually.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   McDonnell Douglas Corp. Douglas Aircraft Co. (automation).andO;Topic:     Computer-Integrated ManufacturingAircraftCost ReductionShop Floor ControlFactory ManagementCase Study.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>